A thin piece of wood of uniform density in the shape of a square with side length $3$ inches weighs $12$ ounces. A second piece of the same type of wood, with the same thickness, also in the shape of a square, has a side length of $6$ inches. Which of the following is closest to the weight, in ounces, of the second piece?
{no choices provided yet}
$\textbf{(A)}\ 24.0\qquad\textbf{(B)}\ 36.0\qquad\textbf{(C)}\ 48.0\qquad\textbf{(D)}\ 60.0\qquad\textbf{(E)}\ 72.0$

A five-digit number (base 8) is squarish if it satisfies the following conditions:
(i) none of its digits are zero;
(ii) it is a perfect square;
(iii) the first two digits, the middle digit, and the last two digits of the number are all perfect squares when considered as two-digit or one-digit numbers in base 8;
(iv) the sum of all its digits is a perfect square.
How many squarish numbers are there?
$\text{(A)} \ 0 \qquad  \text{(B)} \ 1 \qquad  \text{(C)} \ 2 \qquad  \text{(D)} \ 3 \qquad  \text{(E)} \ 4$
$\text{(A)} \ 0 \qquad  \text{(B)} \ 1 \qquad  \text{(C)} \ 2 \qquad  \text{(D)} \ 3 \qquad  \text{(E)} \ 4$
